<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="c515b7a6c1c6143f06a503f2f261924c" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/articles/articles.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/articles/articles.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Shadows, will it Hit or Miss?<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(5.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=16951'>Graham "Graham" Poteet</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=16951&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> October 3, 2004</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> ...A couple of years ago, a certain company named, Decipher, set out to get the Lord of the Rings trademark for a TCG. They did so successfully. They released the first set, that grabbed many card player of all skills and race, age and height.<br />
<br />
<br />
Now we sit back and watch the game go into the eleventh set, Shadows, and see a completely different world.<br />
<br />
Wars is storming onto the TCG scene, players are dropping Lord for other TCGS, because Decipher has in some way or another, messed up the game. X-List, Errata&#39;s, &quot;Rushed Sets&quot; We are all familiar with these, and now the stay true players are hoping for something...<br />
<br />
Will Shadows new gameplay revive the way people look at Lord? This will go in depth on all the info about Shadows, and whether or not Decipher can get this game back in to the glorious card game it once was.<br />
<br />
WILL SHADOWS HIT OR MISS?<br />
<br />
POINT ONE: New Keywords<br />
<br />
A Couple of Examples:<br />
Muster: (Regroup: You may discard a Card from hand to Draw a Card)<br />
Toil: (Exerting certain characters to make stuff cheaper)<br />
Lurker: (Minions with this game text have their skirmishes resolved last)<br />
<br />
Honestly, those look like some new keywords, that alone make the game more strategic.<br />
Muster: Hey, a new, balanced way to cycle. Suddenly fellowships will be able to set up quicker. Running fellowships will benifit from this. Toss a shadow card, hope for a FP card. Or Vice Versa. Swarm now will use this possibly to set up perfect hands. But the first few decks that came to my mind when I saw this kew word.<br />
1. Stupid Swarm<br />
2. Triple Move<br />
3. Lost to the Goblins (That&#39;s Right, Lost to the Goblins)<br />
<br />
You have to remember though, that not all cultures will be getting these keywords, but I know both minions and free peoples will get it. This keyword could change deck building. By giving you more variety of card space. Now instead of needing 4 copies of card, you only need 2 or 3. You can rifle through your cards on the fly...<br />
<br />
But will that really be a good thing? Will someone find a way to make a deck that cycles TOO fast? Galadriels old ring Nenya? Toss 2 in regroup, combined with this? Who knows, maybe this will make Stupid Swarm to stupid, and scare even more people away, or maybe it will change the way you play the game in a good way.<br />
<br />
It will be interesting in Shadows to see how this plays out, it probably will work well, a card&#39;s difference is enough to make or break a single game, but probably not the game as a whole.<br />
<br />
Toil: At first I thought this was a horrible idea. Making stuff cheap, in what is already going to be a relatively cheap site path. But then I found out cards with this game text tend to be pretty good. (Like the Elven version of Gondor Bowmen) I also found out that these cards are EXPENSIVE. That elven version of Gondor Bowmen? 6 Twilight.<br />
6!! But that card has the text Toil 2. In other words for each Elven character you exert while playing it, it&#39;s twiligh cost is -2. Drastic! Choke will probably get some new cards/ideas. But the Shadow will have a way to combat them, by relying on less tokens! Obviously choke decks will get card possibiltys from this, but we will see how this one plays out.<br />
<br />
Lurker: My personal favorite. If they make swarm minions like this that could make that strategy, real painful/popular. Imagine being able to get a &quot;Lurker&quot; on the Ring Bearer. You now have to wait until the end of the rest to fight with him. You&#39;ll have to take threat wounds, you&#39;ll have use pumps before then. With Gimli, you could lose the rest of your companions, then suddenly not be able to add threats and get corrupted! <br />
<br />
This is going to turn some Shadow strategies around. Cards like, Frozen by Fear, my become partialy viable. (Notice I said partialy) Lurkers make assigning even more strategic, and now, you are going to need ways to handle with the possibilty of the Ring Bearer fighting a &quot;Lurker&quot;<br />
<br />
The new keywords definately shed a light of hope, it seems like they are balanced, but we will discover when the set comes out, just how much of an impact they will create.<br />
<br />
<br />
Along with the Keywords decipher has also decided to stick the minion cultures in to a broader range. An interesting move there, which seems like it couold bog down certain decks/cultures. Spotting minions will change now, because they have completely different logos. So now you won&#39;t be able to spot certain minions for cards.<br />
<br />
This will be one of the most interesting to play out, but the simpler shadow cultures now, could draw players to the easierness to pick up the shadow and play it now.<br />
<br />
Oh my gosh, have you heard about these site mechanics? Amazing. GREAT move by decipher. There&#39;s seriously no more throwing a site path together at the last minute before a tourney. Because now, what made LoTR unique in the beginning, is taking new shapes.<br />
You can all go to decipher.com to see the full extent of how this works. But basically there are regions now that you move into, picking the sites as you go along. Don&#39;t have a card to make a site work? That&#39;s ok! Wait for that card, and play that site then. HUGE! People will be waiting on sites, and now path finding cards are going to be very very viable. Having the advantage of playing your sites will be big. But who knows, maybe your opponnent will be able to yuse them to his advantage too. (Sorry decipher, his or her advantage)<br />
<br />
The sites, which is what makes Shadows real unique, will prove to probably be the turning point if this is the set decipher turns it around. I have a stack of sites though that I have to do something with.<br />
<br />
There&#39;s a little bit of a downside though with the release of Shadows, the X-List will be gaining 9 cards.<br />
<br />
Saruman’s Snows (1 C 138)<br />
Sam, Son of Hamfast (1 C 311)<br />
A Talent For Not Being Seen (1 U 316)<br />
Bill Ferny, Swarthy Sneering Fellow (2 R 75)<br />
Gimli, Dwarf of the Mountain Race (2 P 121)<br />
Galadriel, Lady of the Golden Wood (3 R 17)<br />
Legolas, Dauntless Hunter (4 R 73)<br />
Fortress Never Fallen (4 U 276)<br />
Get On and Get Away (4 R 304)<br />
<br />
All of those, whether they be heavy choke, or just overall, too strong cards, are pretty self explanitory if you read the card.<br />
<br />
Snows - Can Make or Break a Game, mad Supid Swarm INSANE<br />
Sam - Took the wagering for first out of the game if you started him or ran mulitple copies, the ultimate Burden Shield<br />
A Talent - Ehhhh I can lean either way.<br />
Ferney - Messes to much with Alt. RB, good call.<br />
Gimli - Many sites coming out are underground, to much choke.<br />
Galadriel - Picking sites with a card like this = too powerful<br />
Legolas - More unbound hobbits being released would&#39;ve meant way too much power.<br />
Fortress Never Fallen - The one decipher says people may be confused about. Decipher states they want Rohan to be Shadow possesion removal heavy, and brute force, not every thing at once.<br />
Get On and Get Away - Too good of a Pathfinder card.<br />
<br />
So there you have it, remember Gondorian Captain? He will be coming off it too, Decipher looks like they may have made the right picks on this recent X-list.<br />
<br />
SOME FINAL PREDICTIONS<br />
Shadows may grab some new players, but maybe not, since it is the 11th set in the game. But with new mechanics some ned players may be swept under and in to the game.<br />
<br />
Shadows may also grab some new players, bringing new mechanics to enchance the game play. It will be interesting to see what player who have gotten out of the game think of these, probably good improvements.<br />
<br />
Shadows will be released after about a month of Wars has been out. Will too many players get sucked into Wars? Only time can tell.<br />
<br />
All in all Shadows is shaping up to be a great set. Shaping new mechanics and re shaping some old stratagies. When we see what effect Shadows has on the scene, is when we can Judge Decipher on whether or not these moves they have made, are correct. Nothing like a good old waiting game. Shadows is a cry for the old enviorment.<br />
<br />
Thanks for reading, take care, Peace Out<br />
<br />
